People praised him during the formal service, highlighting the rich life of service and dedication he had lived.
Are we misguided to exclude the less-flattering memories or details of somebody’s life from a funeral service or the social interactions surrounding it?
Recognizing that other people experienced the dead man as an occasionally mean-spirited or emotionally-disinterested person doesn’t erase the speaker’s sentiments.
She felt like a monster for holding resentment toward a dead man so many people loved and celebrated.
Whether we want it or not, funerals are spaces for learning, not just grieving or reinforcing cultural norms.